{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501124"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:23:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:23:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1721"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1721"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.06,0.35,0.08,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1721"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81322"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1721"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1721"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66664"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"120"},{"type":"tags","id":"2195"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6014"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7191"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44519"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81322"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-month history of painless swelling in his left scrotum. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 3 cm non-tender, smooth-surfaced, uniform swelling at the upper pole of the left testis. The left testis itself feels normal and there is no overlying erythema. The vas deferens can be felt as a distinct entity above the swelling. The right hemiscrotum and its contents feel normal. The mass transilluminates when a light is placed behind it.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epididymal cyst","Varicocele","Hydrocele","Testicular tumour","Inguinoscrotal hernia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of an epididymal cyst. \u003Cstrong\u003EEpididymal cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are fluid-filled swellings that occur within the epididymis, characteristically presenting as smooth, non-tender masses at the superior pole of the testis that transilluminate well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricoceles\u003C/strong\u003E have a characteristic \u0027bag of worms\u0027 texture on palpation and typically become more prominent on standing or with Valsalva manoeuvre, which is not described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydroceles\u003C/strong\u003E also transilluminate but occur anteriorly to the testis between the layers of the tunica vaginalis, rather than at the superior pole. They tend to surround the testis rather than forming a discrete mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETesticular tumours\u003C/strong\u003E typically present as firm, irregular masses within the body of the testis itself, rather than at the superior pole. They do not transilluminate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInguinoscrotal hernias\u003C/strong\u003E can be reduced and the examiner should be able to get above the mass. In this case, the vas deferens is palpable above the mass, making a hernia unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to diagnosis lies in careful scrotal examination, noting the location of the mass relative to the testis, its consistency, and whether it transilluminates. The superior location and smooth consistency, combined with transillumination, are pathognomonic of an epididymal cyst.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Careful inguinoscrotal examination is critical to differentiate between causes of a scrotal mass.","Epididymal cysts present as smooth, non-tender swellings at the upper pole of the testis.","The site of a scrotal mass relative to the testis is key to diagnosis - epididymal cysts occur superiorly, while hydroceles present anteriorly."],"references":["Langan RC, Puente ME. Scrotal masses. Am Fam Physician 2022 Aug;106(2):184-9. Available from: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2022/0800/scrotal-masses.html","Montgomery JS, Bloom DA. The diagnosis and management of scrotal masses. Med Clin N Am 2011 Jan;95(1):235\u201344. DOI: 10.1016/j.mcna.2010.08.029"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66664"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1721"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66664"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-25T20:44:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-25T20:46:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1721"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81322"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43